Experimental procedure
The experiment consisted of a series of test runs. At the start of a test run, the subject grasped the object that was rotated such that the torque had an initial value close to 50 Nrmm. (Figure 1A shows the object in the initial position.) After a 6-s hold phase in which the object was held in a constant position, the subject was verbally instructed to allow the object to rotate slightly to a new angular position. This new position was associated with a smaller tangential torque because of the change in the object’s center of gravity in relation to the digit-object contact area. After being held in this position for 6 s, the object was again rotated slightly to a new position providing an even lower tangential torque. This rotate-andhold sequence was repeated a number of times until the end of the test run, when the object no longer rotated and the tangential torque was close to zero and the rod holding the exchangeable weight pointed downward. Torque target positions were indicated by markers on the circular plate of the test object (n) that could be

