 between 10 and 50 Nrmm. A four-way repeated-measures ANOVA (surface 1 digit 1 tangential force level 1 torque level) with the use of the upper four tangential torque bins (10–50 Nrmm) revealed a reliable main effect of surface [F(2,10) Å 14.73, P õ 0.002]; there were no reliable effects of tangential torque, tangential force, or digit, and no interaction between torque and force. A separate three-way ANOVA (surface 1 digit 1 tangential force level) addressing the range of small torques (0–10 Nrmm) revealed reliable effects of tangential force [F(3,15) Å 5.28, P Å 0.011] and surface [F(2,10) Å 21.4, P õ 0.001] but no effect of digit. The normal force safety margin increased with the slipperiness of the surface material and with tangential force at low tangential torques (Fig. 8A). However, the relative safety margin decreased with tangential force and was smallest with rayon and largest with sandpaper (Fig. 8B). Thus the subject adopted an intermediate strategy between maintaining a constant normal force safety margin across surfaces and maintaining a constant relative safety margin. Models predicting slip force from tangential torque and tangential force Three different mathematical functions were used to model the slip force on the basis of tangential torque and

