The slopes of the regression lines were also inﬂuenced by tangential force ( Fig. 7, A, D, and G ) . The slopes tended to decrease with tangential force. For rayon, the mean slopes were 0.33, 0.30, 0.28, and 0.26 mm01 for tangential forces of 0, 1.2, 2.2, and 3.4 N. The corresponding values with suede were 0.25, 0.22, 0.21, and 0.21 mm01 , and those with sandpaper were 0.11, 0.10, 0.10, and 0.10 mm01 . The results suggest that the effects of tangential force and tangential torque on slip force are not simply additive and that slip force depends to some extent on the interaction of tangential force and torque. Indeed, a signiﬁcant tangential torque 1 tangential force interaction was revealed by a three-way repeated-measures ANOVA ( surface 1 tangential force 1 tangential torque ) [ F ( 12,60 ) Å 3.18, P Å 0.002 ] . In this analysis the effect by tangential torques was accessed by sorting torque data in ﬁve bins Nrmm wide. In addition, there were signiﬁcant main effects by tangential torque [ F ( 4,20 ) Å 731.5, P õ 0.001] , tangential force [ F ( 3,15 ) Å 181.6, P õ 0.001] , and surface material [ F ( 2,10 ) Å 96.5, P õ 0.001] .
